00:49:06.550 --> 00:49:07.216
Other questions?

00:49:18.710 --> 00:49:20.430
So this is really a
famous Hamiltonian.

00:49:23.190 --> 00:49:25.490
And you also see how
natural the definition

00:49:25.490 --> 00:49:28.180
of the single-photon
Rabi frequency.

00:49:28.180 --> 00:49:33.010
So we have one half h bar
omega for the diagonal sigma z

00:49:33.010 --> 00:49:33.680
matrix.

00:49:33.680 --> 00:49:35.280
This is the atomic excitation.

00:49:35.280 --> 00:49:38.740
This is the unperturbed
Hamiltonian of the atom.

00:49:38.740 --> 00:49:41.290
This is the unperturbed
Hamiltonian of the photon.

00:49:41.290 --> 00:49:43.340
And now the two are coupled.

00:49:43.340 --> 00:49:46.640
And the coupling is a
product of an operator acting

00:49:46.640 --> 00:49:50.250
on the photon field
plus minus one photon.

00:49:50.250 --> 00:49:54.730
And the other one is an
operator acting on the atoms.

00:49:54.730 --> 00:49:58.910
And it is plus, minus,
and atomic excitation.

00:49:58.910 --> 00:50:01.570
So let me just
remind you of that.

00:50:01.570 --> 00:50:04.130
The sigma plus and
sigma minus operator.

00:50:07.320 --> 00:50:09.620
The sigma plus is the
atomic raising operator,

00:50:09.620 --> 00:50:12.440
which takes a ground
to the excited state.

00:50:12.440 --> 00:50:17.360
And the sigma minus operator is
the atomic lowering operator,

00:50:17.360 --> 00:50:19.910
which takes the atom from the
excited to the ground state.

00:50:23.450 --> 00:50:24.860
So this is our Hamiltonian.

00:50:28.696 --> 00:50:34.500
And to hear about space on
which this Hamiltonian acts

00:50:34.500 --> 00:50:38.520
is the product
space of the atom.

00:50:38.520 --> 00:50:43.050
Direct product of the
states of the light.

00:50:46.080 --> 00:50:49.310
Or in other words,
the basis state

00:50:49.310 --> 00:50:53.360
would be that we
use for the atoms.

00:50:53.360 --> 00:50:57.700
The states which have zero
or one quantum of excitation.

00:50:57.700 --> 00:51:02.110
So we use excited
state or ground state.

00:51:02.110 --> 00:51:08.500
And for the photon, we can
just use the Fock states

00:51:08.500 --> 00:51:13.140
where the occupation
number is n.

00:51:13.140 --> 00:51:14.510
Questions about that?

00:51:19.980 --> 00:51:25.860
So it's a very-- just look
at it with some enjoyment

00:51:25.860 --> 00:51:27.100
for a few seconds.

00:51:27.100 --> 00:51:31.970
I mean, this is a Hamiltonian,
which has just a few terms.

00:51:31.970 --> 00:51:33.640
But what is behind
it is, of course,

00:51:33.640 --> 00:51:35.560
a power of all the definitions.

00:51:35.560 --> 00:51:37.980
I mean, each symbol
has so much meaning.

00:51:37.980 --> 00:51:44.360
But in the end, by having
this formalism of operators

00:51:44.360 --> 00:51:46.570
quantized electromagnetic field.

00:51:46.570 --> 00:51:52.170
We can write down-- we can
catch many, many aspects

00:51:52.170 --> 00:51:55.640
or we can, pretty much, fully
describe how a two level

00:51:55.640 --> 00:51:58.510
system interacts a quantized
electromagnetic field

00:51:58.510 --> 00:52:00.646
with that set of equations.

00:52:03.420 --> 00:52:07.340
Of course, the fact is not
that everything is so simple.

00:52:07.340 --> 00:52:11.200
The fact is that we have, by
understanding the physics,

00:52:11.200 --> 00:52:13.410
we have skillfully
made definitions,

00:52:13.410 --> 00:52:17.160
which allow us to
write everything down

00:52:17.160 --> 00:52:18.205
in this compact form.

00:52:20.730 --> 00:52:23.380
So often something is
simple to write down.

00:52:23.380 --> 00:52:26.050
But if there's a lot
of physics insight,

00:52:26.050 --> 00:52:28.470
we spend some time
in discussing it.

00:52:28.470 --> 00:52:31.380
And the first thing I want
to just point out and discuss

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:33.730
is this interaction term.

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:36.240
We have the product of
sigma plus and sigma

00:52:36.240 --> 00:52:39.560
minus with a and a dagger.

00:52:39.560 --> 00:52:43.724
So what we have here is we
have an interaction term.

00:52:48.230 --> 00:53:00.320
And this interaction part
has actually four terms

00:53:00.320 --> 00:53:03.494
in a very natural way.

00:53:03.494 --> 00:53:06.960
Well, let me just
write them down.

00:53:06.960 --> 00:53:12.080
It's sigma plus with a.

00:53:12.080 --> 00:53:14.260
Sigma minus with a dagger.

00:53:17.330 --> 00:53:20.490
Sigma plus with a dagger.

00:53:20.490 --> 00:53:25.590
And sigma minus with a.

00:53:25.590 --> 00:53:29.880
OK, so let's discuss those.

00:53:29.880 --> 00:53:33.050
Sigma plus with a dagger.

00:53:33.050 --> 00:53:38.980
Sigma plus is actually
an absorption process.

00:53:38.980 --> 00:53:44.850
a reduces the photo
number by one,

00:53:44.850 --> 00:53:48.860
and increases the
atomic excitation

00:53:48.860 --> 00:53:50.560
from the column to
the excited state.

00:53:56.120 --> 00:54:01.790
The other term looks naturally,
intuitively like emission.

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:06.690
The a dagger operator takes
us from n to n plus 1.

00:54:06.690 --> 00:54:10.800
And sigma minus takes us
from the excited state

00:54:10.800 --> 00:54:13.820
to the current state.

00:54:13.820 --> 00:54:16.580
So these are the
two terms, which

00:54:16.580 --> 00:54:25.590
we would call intuitive terms
because they make sense.

00:54:25.590 --> 00:54:29.050
The other terms are
somewhat more tricky.

00:54:29.050 --> 00:54:34.450
Sigma plus and a dagger
means we create a photon

00:54:34.450 --> 00:54:37.240
and we create an excitation.

00:54:37.240 --> 00:54:40.530
So in other words, it's not
that, like the other term,

00:54:40.530 --> 00:54:44.110
quantum of excitation disappears
from the field, appears

00:54:44.110 --> 00:54:46.080
in the atom, and vice versa.

00:54:46.080 --> 00:54:52.150
Sigma plus a dagger means
we have an atom excitation

00:54:52.150 --> 00:54:55.980
takes us from the ground
to the excited state.

00:54:55.980 --> 00:54:59.600
Plus, we emit a photon
at the same time.

00:54:59.600 --> 00:55:02.520
And sigma minus a
dagger means that we

00:55:02.520 --> 00:55:05.470
go from the excited
to the ground state.

00:55:05.470 --> 00:55:09.065
So we have an atom d excitation.

00:55:09.065 --> 00:55:10.530
And I would say,
well, if the atom

00:55:10.530 --> 00:55:13.990
is d excited it
should emit a photon.

00:55:13.990 --> 00:55:20.765
But instead, the
photon disappears.

00:55:27.140 --> 00:55:31.170
So we have those processes.

00:55:31.170 --> 00:55:37.520
The last two are
sometimes referred to

00:55:37.520 --> 00:55:39.490
in the theoretical literature.

00:55:39.490 --> 00:55:42.450
They are off shell.

00:55:42.450 --> 00:55:44.750
Under shell is
energy conservation.

00:55:44.750 --> 00:55:48.860
Off shell means they
cannot conserve energy.

00:55:48.860 --> 00:55:51.510
But nevertheless,
these are terms

00:55:51.510 --> 00:55:52.855
which appear in the operator.

00:55:57.828 --> 00:56:00.385
But you should be used to
if you have often terms

00:56:00.385 --> 00:56:03.900
in the operator which cannot
drive a resonant transition.

00:56:03.900 --> 00:56:07.740
When you looked at the DC
stock effect or when we looked

00:56:07.740 --> 00:56:10.970
at the AC stock effect
for low frequency photons,

00:56:10.970 --> 00:56:13.945
those low frequency photons
cannot excite an atom

00:56:13.945 --> 00:56:15.960
to the excited state.

00:56:15.960 --> 00:56:18.960
So they are not
causing a transition,

00:56:18.960 --> 00:56:22.500
but they led to energy shifts
in second order perturbation

00:56:22.500 --> 00:56:25.260
theory.

00:56:25.260 --> 00:56:32.280
So therefore, those terms
this language now cannot drive

00:56:32.280 --> 00:56:33.340
transitions.

00:56:33.340 --> 00:56:37.111
They can only drive transitions
to virtual states, which

00:56:37.111 --> 00:56:39.610
would mean they can only appear
in second order perturbation

00:56:39.610 --> 00:56:42.840
theory that you go up to
a so-called virtual state

00:56:42.840 --> 00:56:45.460
but you immediately go down.

00:56:45.460 --> 00:56:49.590
And those terms give
only rise to shifts.

00:56:53.740 --> 00:56:56.230
No transitions because you
couldn't conserve energy

00:56:56.230 --> 00:56:57.750
in the transition.

00:56:57.750 --> 00:57:00.540
But you can do shifts
in second order.

00:57:05.010 --> 00:57:07.850
And one example, which we
discussed in the clicker

00:57:07.850 --> 00:57:16.720
question is that those shifts
are actually lamb shifts.

00:57:16.720 --> 00:57:19.770
And in other places,
especially in the context

00:57:19.770 --> 00:57:29.770
of microwave fields, they are
called Bloch-Siegert shifts

00:57:29.770 --> 00:57:35.380
And let's just look
at one specific state.

00:57:35.380 --> 00:57:39.030
And this is the simplest of all.

00:57:39.030 --> 00:57:42.670
We have the vacuum no photons.

00:57:42.670 --> 00:57:45.980
And the atom is in
the ground state.

00:57:45.980 --> 00:57:49.380
If you look at the
four possibilities

00:57:49.380 --> 00:57:54.830
of the interaction term, there
is only one non vanishing term.

00:57:54.830 --> 00:57:58.220
The photon is at the bottom
off all possible states.

00:57:58.220 --> 00:58:01.890
The atom is at the bottom
of the possible states.

00:58:01.890 --> 00:58:04.250
So when we act with
the four terms on it,

00:58:04.250 --> 00:58:05.820
the only term which
contributes is

00:58:05.820 --> 00:58:08.360
where those is where
those are raised

00:58:08.360 --> 00:58:09.840
because all the others are 0.

00:58:13.490 --> 00:58:23.120
The only non vanishing
term is where

00:58:23.120 --> 00:58:30.030
we create a virtual
atomic excitation and also

00:58:30.030 --> 00:58:34.090
a virtual excitation
of the photon field.

00:58:34.090 --> 00:58:37.870
And we know that when we
have an atom in the ground

00:58:37.870 --> 00:58:42.650
state in the vacuum that
the only manifestation

00:58:42.650 --> 00:58:45.600
of the electromagnetic
field is, of course, not

00:58:45.600 --> 00:58:47.720
spontaneous emission
but the lamb shift.

00:58:51.760 --> 00:58:56.050
So therefore, if you
would apply this operator

00:58:56.050 --> 00:58:59.910
to the bound state of
an electron in an atom,

00:58:59.910 --> 00:59:04.550
the complicated 1s wave
function of hydrogen and sum

00:59:04.550 --> 00:59:08.500
this operator over all modes
of the electromagnetic field.

00:59:08.500 --> 00:59:12.070
Then you would have done
a first principle QED

00:59:12.070 --> 00:59:14.500
calculation of the lamb shift.

00:59:14.500 --> 00:59:16.480
I'm not doing it but
you should understand

00:59:16.480 --> 00:59:20.490
that this operator--
sigma plus a dagger--

00:59:20.490 --> 00:59:23.052
is you operator
for the Lamb shift.

